Added fact: Zip2 was Elon’s first real company that “provided and licensed online city guide software to newspapers. The company was founded in Palo Alto, California as Global Link Information Network in 1995.” When it was sold in 1999, Elon made $22m he used to build his empire.

Thus, being the 2nd coming of Rupert Murdoch, whose era is coming to an end sooner than later, makes a lot of sense. Yep: Uncle Satan, The Sequel.
(Okay, back to watching Sylvester Stallone in “Samaritan,” in which who is good and who is evil are unclear. Get it?)

Added bonus: The cockamamier the better in right wing media, especially using words like EXPLOSIVE! SECRET! PLOT TO TAKE AWAY OUR [fill in the angry blank] RIGHTS! Also LIBS, SOROS, and, yes, FAUCI SUCKS. Don’t forget Elon fave: PEDO. A whole new world of wacky conspiracies!

Meshing it all might be an easier way to gain some much desired path around what that whole gang derisively call MSM. As Elon knows, he can build all the rockets and cars he wants, but the real power is in owning media that you control to push whatever cockamamie agenda you have.

Companies like Substack needs an exit at some point. This is why Musk said he was open to buying it recently. It also scratches the itch AH has to makes its own media. It tried with Future, but that sucked wind and recently was shuttered. Making media is hard, as it turns out!

Such as a more robust newsletter than Twitter’s shitty effort with its Revue acquisition like the Andreessen Horowitz funded Substack, whose big valuation has got to be hurting about now. Still, it has a strong roster of right-leaning writers who have built decent wee businesses.

A news distribution and creation company is what the Twitter platform always should have been aiming for, as it is its genuine nature. Using that critical building block, it makes sense to start adding other pieces on the cheap. And everything in media is indeed cheap now.

Enter Twitter, which though smaller than Meta & TikTok, lives rent free in the minds of journalists, pols and the new noisemakers of the current partisan era as the place to read, digest and vomit up hot takes on news. It’s the current news mosh pit for better and now for worse.

Today, it makes a ton of dough and has built a loyal audience that is there for the taking and with no real competition. Other networks like OAN and NewsMax are sucking wind, while the social networks like Truth Social and Parler are too small to make a dent.

Now they cannot shut up about their issues of being censored and not able to promote their warped version of free speech. Sound familiar? Well, that is what sounds like Fox News, which is currently vulnerable to a newcomer that is built from the digital ground up.

Even if it costs $$ in the interim, having a powerful media property has been the wet dream of the aggrieved tech bro set for a while. They hated it when the once slavish reporters started to question their hegemony and their persistent victim mentality has only gotten worse.

The old way Twitter was built as ad-supported business within tweets sucks, so torching the old to build a new media biz makes sense as does pissing on certain advertisers. So does laying waste to the old employee base, in order to attract a new one.

Stick with me here — I am sitting on an airplane to SF which gives me a chance to ruminate on the why-so-loud-and-screamy of late, when the real goal should be to quietly rebuild the product, cut costs and eventually take the whole mess public again for his legions of fanboys.

So tomorrow on @pivotpod, I posit a theory about why Musk has become so performative with his right-wing dog whistle tweets on Fauci, libs, wokeness, as well as his pushing out the Twitter Files as if he were Woodward & Bernstein: Maybe he’s building a new kind of media company.

Respecting your audience and your agreement with them is the only way. That’s why I also have been stressing IP ownership of what I make. Most of my work over the years — much of which is still thankful discoverable — but the only one who will truly take care of what I make is me https://t.co/hrC4wIJhrz

WYSIWYG is my general rule on most things. You need to always ask and ask audience again and again as Steve Jobs said to Walt and I in a famous interview about privacy. You must stress disclosure (we had long ones on ATD) and make clear what you are doing with their data and more https://t.co/JNoEYfw2Ua

As I often reiterate, it should be consumer’s choice and you cannot shake your finger in news stories at all kinds of tech companies for doing this kind of thing if you do it or make elaborate excuses of why it is different. It is not. https://t.co/7OK8raQnIM

We objected since we feared all the links broken and disappeared years of content forever. It was also disingenuous to do since people were searching for us and got them. What a crap way to treat audience, not to give them what they were looking for but what suited marketing. https://t.co/7sZ9xmzvH6

You can find links to the endless scoops & wonderful work by the stellar ATD staff on OTHER sites, but when you click, you get error after error. And where are the pieces? Who the fuck knows. I was so worried about this happening in 2013 that I yelled a lot. It was the right call https://t.co/LYHb55N6qP

The same is true of almost all the articles that were supposed to be preserved when the minions of Rupert Murdoch declined to let us buy our work back or assure us it would not disappear. The intent seemed to be to resolve to random WSJ tech pages to goose their traffic with ours https://t.co/DVJxzfIT3P

While they seem to exist at WSJ Video site, when you click on any link you get an error message over and over. The one that breaks my heart is a 9 minute video I did in 2009 at SurveyMonkey with Dave Goldberg , the wonderful tech exec (and my friend) who died unexpectedly in 2015 https://t.co/WK8EO7Txdc

Everyone now famous, infamous & just plain gone is in those videos, which was supposed to be stored forever in an agreement made with the WSJ & News Corp. when @waltmossberg & I left to start out on our own in 2013. We had offered to buy them all, as well as the ATD feed. https://t.co/jDZBZ8VRMx

Stumbly, bumbly and painfully awkward, for sure, but I can still recall his steely tone that presaged all that was to come. It was all there. So too a long and testy video I did with Peter Thiel early on, in which we argued and he showed many of the cards that were to come. https://t.co/vdAAPhZWhB

That included the time I ambushed Mark Zuckerberg when he wandered into my lunch at Il Fornaio in Palo Alto. Facebook was struggling at the time, so @jimihendrixlive dragged him in to make nice and I asked him a raft of questions on camera, including if he was going to sell. https://t.co/3fnKW2Yz51

This was important since I used to use my Flip video (RIP) to record off the cuff and in your face interviews with the young & poorer versions of the current crop of Internet billionaire moguls. It was fun and raw and revealing. It was history in real time. https://t.co/7YV4HDNhlD

We were never sorry for that as the WSJ system at the time was just shitty and Matt has been a true entrepreneur in this arena who understood the needs of journalists. At the time in 2007, there were very rudimentary ways to post videos. We used Brightcove, which I cursed daily. https://t.co/oze76ZuB2D

If you remember, in the movie “The Social Network,” it was said the Internet is written in inedible ink. As it turns out, it’s not. When we started ATD inside the Wall Street Journal many years ago, after many bake-offs we picked @photomatt & @WordPress as our publishing platform https://t.co/9sUariwrV7

This is a thread on the ephemeral nature of content, who owns your work & why creators need to own their IP, which just hit home when I was doing research for my memoir on covering the rise of Silicon Valley. Why? Because most the work we did at All Things Digital has gone poof. https://t.co/4dOXoD7sro

This was a man in our lives for 20 years and I thought 20 years more once we were able to get back to the city we so love when this pandemic was over. We were excited to maybe be able to do that this summer & to walk into Sami’s to say hello again to our old and dear friend.  RIP

But here’s what lasts: Sami raised my kids, giving them intangible lessons about dignity, kindness, humor &, most of all, love. He also gave them chips & milk & once the most delicious figs they ever tasted. No more, but that’s not what matters. What matters is that we remember.

He was the very quintessence of the word essential, but in the end — the very end — was sacrificial. This pandemic has taken so many with so many similar dreams, who deserved so much more from a country that let them down terribly. Losing Sami was tragic and also avoidable.

The day before he got sick, Sami had just bought another small store nearby in the neighborhood because he believed in the place and its people and in the future. He kept his indispensable store open always, serving the community with a generosity of spirit that was inspiring.

I last saw Sami when I introduced him to our newborn daughter over the 2019-2020 holiday. He promised her then that she’d get the same walk in hungry, walk out with a treat wonderful life my oldest had been gifted by this truly excellent man. Deepest condolences to his family.

The passing Sami Bsisso from COVID leaves our family & our longtime neighborhood in the Castro bereft. His wonderful general store is the place where my 2 sons grew up knowing that his loving kindness, generous spirit and endless ice cream cones was just always across the street. https://t.co/VaS14OUP8P
